<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How is 0-60 mph time calculated?", answer: "The 0-60 mph time is estimated using the power-to-weight ratio (vehicle weight divided by horsepower). The formula uses an empirical model where time = (weight/hp)^0.75 * 0.95, adjusted for drivetrain type and tire grip. AWD vehicles are typically 10% faster than RWD, and performance tires improve times by up to 10% compared to all-season tires." },
  { question: "What is the quarter mile time formula?", answer: "The quarter mile time is estimated using the Roger Huntington formula: ET = 6.290 * (weight/hp)^(1/3). The trap speed at the end of the quarter mile is calculated as Speed = 224 / (weight/hp)^(1/3). These formulas provide good estimates for naturally aspirated vehicles and are reasonably accurate for modern turbocharged cars as well." },
  { question: "How does drivetrain affect 0-60 time?", answer: "Drivetrain significantly affects launch performance. AWD vehicles can put power down more effectively from a standstill, typically achieving 0-60 times about 10% faster than equivalent RWD vehicles. FWD vehicles are about 5% slower due to weight transfer lifting the driven wheels during hard acceleration, causing wheelspin." },
  { question: "What is a good power-to-weight ratio?", answer: "For passenger cars, a power-to-weight ratio under 10 lbs/hp is considered sports car territory (sub-5 second 0-60). A ratio of 10-15 lbs/hp is sporty, 15-20 is average, and above 20 is considered slow. Supercars achieve ratios of 4-6 lbs/hp, while economy cars are typically 20-30 lbs/hp." },
  { question: "Why do real 0-60 times differ from calculated estimates?", answer: "Calculated estimates cannot account for all variables. Real-world performance depends on launch technique, transmission type and shift speed, turbo lag, traction control settings, road surface condition, altitude and air temperature, and vehicle-specific power delivery characteristics. These estimates are most accurate for naturally aspirated rear-wheel-drive vehicles with manual transmissions." }
]) %>

