    <article class="prose dark:prose-invert max-w-none">
      <h2>How to Use the Zero to Sixty Calculator</h2>
      <p>
        Our zero to sixty calculator estimates your vehicle's acceleration performance using physics-based models. Enter your vehicle's horsepower, curb weight in pounds, drivetrain type, and tire type. The calculator computes the estimated 0-60 mph time, 0-30 mph time, quarter mile elapsed time, quarter mile trap speed, and power-to-weight ratio. These estimates give you a solid baseline for comparing vehicles or understanding your car's performance potential.
      </p>
      <p>
        The estimates use empirical formulas refined against real-world performance data. The 0-60 calculation factors in power-to-weight ratio with adjustments for drivetrain traction advantages and tire grip levels. The quarter mile estimates use the respected Roger Huntington formula used by automotive engineers and enthusiasts for decades.
      </p>

      <div class="my-6"><%= render "shared/ad_slot", slot: "in_content" %></div>

      <h2>Understanding Vehicle Performance</h2>
      <p>
        Vehicle acceleration is fundamentally determined by the relationship between power and weight. A lightweight car with moderate horsepower can outperform a heavy car with more power. The power-to-weight ratio, measured in pounds per horsepower, is the single most important predictor of straight-line acceleration. Lower numbers mean better performance, with supercars typically achieving 4-6 lbs/hp and economy cars sitting at 20-30 lbs/hp.
      </p>

      <h3>The Role of Drivetrain</h3>
      <p>
        Drivetrain configuration significantly impacts how effectively a vehicle puts its power to the ground during acceleration. All-wheel drive distributes torque to all four tires, maximizing traction and reducing wheelspin during launch. This is why AWD vehicles typically achieve faster 0-60 times than equivalent RWD or FWD models, especially in less-than-ideal conditions. However, AWD systems add weight, which can offset some of the traction advantage at higher speeds.
      </p>

      <h3>Tire Grip Matters</h3>
      <p>
        Tires are the only contact point between your vehicle and the road, making them crucial for acceleration performance. Performance tires with soft, sticky compounds can shave significant time off 0-60 runs by reducing wheelspin. The difference between winter tires and performance summer tires on a powerful car can be over a full second in 0-60 time. Even switching from all-season to summer tires typically improves launch performance by 5-10%.
      </p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>How is 0-60 mph time calculated?</h3>
      <p>The 0-60 mph time is estimated using the power-to-weight ratio. The formula uses time = (weight/hp)^0.75 * 0.95, adjusted for drivetrain type and tire grip. AWD vehicles are typically 10% faster than RWD.</p>

      <h3>What is the quarter mile time formula?</h3>
      <p>The quarter mile time uses the Roger Huntington formula: ET = 6.290 * (weight/hp)^(1/3). The trap speed is Speed = 224 / (weight/hp)^(1/3).</p>

      <h3>How does drivetrain affect 0-60 time?</h3>
      <p>AWD vehicles achieve 0-60 times about 10% faster than equivalent RWD vehicles. FWD vehicles are about 5% slower due to weight transfer during hard acceleration.</p>

      <h3>What is a good power-to-weight ratio?</h3>
      <p>Under 10 lbs/hp is sports car territory, 10-15 is sporty, 15-20 is average, and above 20 is considered slow.</p>

      <h3>Why do real 0-60 times differ from estimates?</h3>
      <p>Real-world performance depends on launch technique, transmission type, turbo lag, traction control, road surface, altitude, air temperature, and vehicle-specific power delivery characteristics.</p>

